        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer115638467" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4293768417863934184">(2010)<br/><i>American Rust</i> is a great title. And it summarizes effectively the human drama Philipp Myer chronicles in this novel. In spite of some flaws, the work captures the tragedies and sentimental comedies of life in the rusting (read “dying”) towns of the Northeast, including south west Pennsylvania. In addition, Myer intertwines effectively the lives of the primary characters with the physical and built environments of that area. It is a skillfully crafted first novel.<br/><br/>The ending is slightly disa</span>
  <span id="freeText4293768417863934184" style="display:none">(2010)<br /><i>American Rust</i> is a great title. And it summarizes effectively the human drama Philipp Myer chronicles in this novel. In spite of some flaws, the work captures the tragedies and sentimental comedies of life in the rusting (read “dying”) towns of the Northeast, including south west Pennsylvania. In addition, Myer intertwines effectively the lives of the primary characters with the physical and built environments of that area. It is a skillfully crafted first novel.<br /><br />The ending is slightly disappointing, unexpected given the directness of the introspections of the major characters. The pages before, however, are not disappointing.<br /><br />(2022)<br />I first read <i>American Rust</i> in 2010, well before America's simmering social segmentation flamed into the public's consciousness during and after Trump's presidency. Re-reading it in 2022, I echo Scott Galupo's 2016 suggestion: "You should add <i>American Rust</i> to your Trumplandia reading list."</span>
  <a data-text-id="4293768417863934184" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


